[Student "S"]
{SOUTH has just 11 points, not enough to open the bidding. 
But when NORTH opens 1\S SOUTH should show her "almost opening strength" 
by jumping to 3\S.

NORTH has just 13 points, and knowing SOUTH has less than 13 he passes.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:T82.AK753.KQ5.Q6 KQJ4.T.JT743.T84 73.Q8642.A86.K95 A965.J9.92.AJ732"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "25d40ccc510a3b2f55be9125eff6c4e01b7b16d4de9259b5cf1d2f440389290b"]
[Category "Partnership Bidding"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "partnership_bidding/basic_bidding"]
[Student "S"]
{After EAST opens with 1\H, WEST has a small "dilemma". 
With 11 points she really is only strong enough to make a jump raise to 3\H. 
But, with five trumps the hand deserves more. So she just bids 4\H instead.

Usually, no matter what your strength, when you have five cards in the Major suit that your partner opens 
with you should just jump right to game.}

